abstract: Critics and writers for The New York Times recommend New Yearâ€™s Eve pop music events in the city.
snippet: Critics and writers for The New York Times recommend New Yearâ€™s Eve pop music events in the city.
lead_paragraph: Itâ€™s over. Itâ€™s a wrap. Nothing more to see here. The damage is done. Finis. These are the lies we tell ourselves on New Yearâ€™s Eve, a holiday that ostensibly celebrates renewal but really places an arbitrary cap on a yearâ€™s worth of love and hurt and strife and joy and seals it, freeing up space to try again, once the ball drops. Going out on New Yearâ€™s Eve, then â€” thatâ€™s really for the people who want that jar sealed tight. They want to rage, to get lost in shamanistic fever, to laugh until the body doesnâ€™t know how else to move. Here, writers for The New York Times weigh in on events that, for some, may fill a need for a sense of finality but that are also a reminder that even after the worst, life goes on. JON CARAMANICA
